│ The repeated failures of my previous attempts, including very aggressive patches to disable horizontal reduction vectorization, strongly suggest that the problematic transformation is  │
│ not happening where I thought it was. The vectorization from a scalar DAG to a vector reduction is still occurring, which means there must be another mechanism at play.                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The core issue is the unsound transformation of a short-circuiting scalar computation into a vectorized form that evaluates all operands, thereby incorrectly propagating `poison`. The  │
│ scalar expression is equivalent to `(%x > 1) || (%b > 1) || (%c > 1) || (%d > 1)`. The vectorizer correctly identifies the four `icmp` instructions as candidates for vectorization. The │
│ problem lies in how it handles the subsequent logic.                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Given that my attempts to block this in `isHorReduction` and `isVectorizableHorReduction` failed, I will now look at the code that *builds* the reduction. The function                  │
│ `vectorizeHorReduction` in `SLPVectorizer.cpp` is responsible for creating the vectorized reduction code (e.g., the `llvm.vector.reduce.or` intrinsic call).                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will apply a direct and unmistakable patch to this function. I will modify `vectorizeHorReduction` to immediately return `nullptr` if it is asked to create a reduction for an `OR`    │
│ operation on `i1` types. This will unconditionally prevent the generation of the faulty code. This is a heavy-handed approach, but it serves as a crucial diagnostic step. If this patch │
│ succeeds, it proves the problem originates from the call to `vectorizeHorReduction`, and the failure of previous patches was due to them being in the wrong place to stop the chain of   │
│ events leading to this call.                                                                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The code to add at the beginning of `vectorizeHorReduction` is:                                                                                                                          │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│ if (H->getOpcode() == Instruction::Or && H->getSplatValue()->getType()->isIntegerTy(1))                                                                                                  │
│   return nullptr;                                                                                                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ This checks if the reduction is an `OR` and if the scalar type is `i1`. If so, it aborts the vectorization of this reduction. I will use `sed` to insert this code into                  │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`.                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
