│ This miscompilation has proven to be exceptionally difficult to fix, with numerous attempts failing to prevent the incorrect vectorization. The core issue is the unsound transformation │
│ of a short-circuiting `select` into a logical `or`, which does not respect `poison` semantics. The persistence of the problem suggests that the transformation is happening in a code    │
│ path that I have not yet successfully modified.                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ After exhausting many other possibilities, I am returning to my first and most logical hypothesis: the flaw is in the `isHorReduction` function in `SLPVectorizer.cpp`, where a `select  │
│ i1 C, i1 true, i1 V` instruction is treated as `C or V`. My previous attempts to patch this location failed, which was perplexing. I will make one final, carefully constructed attempt  │
│ to fix it here.                                                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Instead of deleting code or adding complex checks, I will modify the logic to be poison-aware. The transformation is only valid if the `false` value of the `select` (`V`) is guaranteed │
│ not to be poison. I will add a check for this using `isGuaranteedNotToBePoison`. If the value might be poison, the function will return `nullptr`, rejecting the reduction pattern. This │
│ is the correct and most precise way to fix this soundness bug without being overly restrictive.                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will use a `sed` command to replace the original `if` condition with a new one that includes the poison check. This avoids the ambiguity of multi-line deletions and ensures the logic │
│ is correctly inserted.                                                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i 's/if (C->isOne() && ROKind == RecurKind::Or) {/if (C->isOne() \&\& ROKind == RecurKind::Or) {\n          if (!isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(SI->getFalseValue(), AC, SI, DT))\n      │
│ return nullptr;/' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp && sed -i '37a #include "llvm/Analysis/ValueTracking.h"' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp               │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
