│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ My previous attempts, including very aggressive ones, have all failed. Disabling the `i1` `OR` reduction in `getReductionCost` caused widespread failures in the test suite, indicating  │
│ that this was too broad and broke many valid vectorizations. The original miscompilation, however, was not fixed, which is extremely puzzling.                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This implies that the vectorization is happening through a path that does not involve `getReductionCost` in the way I expected. The SLP vectorizer is a complex, multi-stage process.    │
│ The bottom-up vectorizer (`BoUpSLP`) first vectorizes seed instructions and then tries to vectorize their users.                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The core of the problem is the transformation of `select C, true, V` into `C or V`. This is unsafe with `poison`. I will make one final, highly targeted attempt to fix this. I will go  │
│ back to the `isHorReduction` function. My previous attempts to patch it failed, but it remains the most logical place for this transformation to be recognized. The failure of previous  │
│ patches might have been due to subtle errors in the `sed` commands or an incomplete understanding of the surrounding code.                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ I will add a check that is both simple and robust. Inside the `case Instruction::Select:` block of `isHorReduction`, I will specifically look for the pattern `select i1, i1 true, i1`   │
│ and immediately return `nullptr` if it is found and the reduction kind is `OR`. This is a very specific pattern match that should only affect the problematic case and similar ones,     │
│ without the widespread collateral damage of my previous attempt.                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                                                                                   │
│       if (auto *C = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(SI->getTrueValue())) {                                                                                                                         │
│         if (C->isOne() && ROKind == RecurKind::Or) {                                                                                                                                     │
│           // This transformation is unsound w.r.t. poison.                                                                                                                               │
│           // select C, true, V  is not  C | V                                                                                                                                            │
│           // if C=true and V=poison.                                                                                                                                                     │
│           return nullptr;                                                                                                                                                                │
│         }                                                                                                                                                                                │
│       }                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
│ I will use `sed` to insert `return nullptr;` directly into the block that matches this pattern. This is the cleanest and most direct way to disable this specific, unsound               │
│ transformation.                                                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '/if (C->isOne() && ROKind == RecurKind::Or) {/a \          return nullptr;' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
